  "text": "When β = 1 this is the Drury-Arveson space, which is strictly smaller than the classical Hardy space on the ball but often the more appropriate setting for multivariable operator theory; see e.g. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . When β = m we obtain the classical Hardy space and β = m + 1 gives the Bergman space. This scale of spaces can be extended to non-integral values of β via Calderon interpolation, and all of the results of this paper are valid for this larger scale. However since the primary values of interest are β = 1, m and m + 1, we omit the details.",
